[ProMED-mail thanks Panduranga Rao for these communications.

The report of a case of polio due to infection with a vaccine-derived poliovirus (VDPV) in a country is always a concern as the possibility of circulating VDPVs (cVDPV) is there, an indication of pockets of low vaccination coverage that permit the circulation of these viruses.

In the newswire report above, there is mention of the possibility that this case may represent an immunodeficiency related VDPV infection, and not represent an infection with a cVDPV.

According to the latest information on the India National Polio Surveillance Project website:

Vaccine derived polioviruses
- A vaccine-derived poliovirus (VDPV) has been confirmed in a 10 month old boy in Dharur block of Beed district in [Maharashtra]. VDPVs are extremely rare and occur in children with immunodeficiency or in populations with low levels of immunization.
- This is the 3rd case of VDPV in 2013. Earlier, VDPV was reported in an 8 month old boy in a village in Jaipatna block of Kalahandi district of Odisha and a 5 month old girl in Kako block of Jehanabad district of Bihar. All 3 cases are of VDPV type 2.
- In 2012, VDPV was reported in an immunodeficient child in Murshidabad district of West Bengal. In 2011, 7 cases of VDPVs were reported -- 3 in children with immune deficiency in Dhamtari (Chhattisgarh), Barnala (Punjab), and Jajpur (Odisha) and 4 in areas with low routine immunization coverage in Udaipur (Rajasthan), Ghaziabad, and Badaun (Uttar Pradesh) and Vidisha (Madhya Pradesh).
- The Government of India and the States have been effectively responding to the VDPVs in the past. The response to VDPVs that are detected in areas with low routine immunization coverage involve conducting catch up routine vaccination campaigns. The response is consistent with the global strategy. As a result, none of the VDPVs detected in India during the past 3 years have shown any evidence of circulation.
- In the current situation of polio eradication, an importation of wild poliovirus remains the larger threat to the children in India. OPV has reduced the polio incidence globally by greater than 99 per cent and has helped India stop transmission of wild poliovirus. India has not reported any case of polio for over 2 years, the last case being in January 2011. (The full report is available at http://www.npspindia.org/VDPV.doc).

We await more information on the final classification of the type of VDPV in this case -- immunodeficiency related, circulating, or ambiguous. (This moderator was hoping there might be more specific information to report on this case prior to posting, but alas, not.)

For a map of locations within India where VDPVs have been identified see http://www.npspindia.org/Polio11.asp.

For a map of India showing states, see http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/india/india-political-map.htm. For the HealthMap/ProMED map of India, see http://healthmap.org/r/1*Oa. - Mod.MPP]
